---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Eight parties, five behaviours · Riksdag Revealed"
  description="The 2022-26 Riksdag mandate read by behaviour. Eight parties on the ballot resolve to five behavioural entities in the chamber record, with the four-party Tidö bloc forming during the mandate. Roll-call votes, reservations, speeches and manifestos as evidence."
>
  <article class="container">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Riksdag Revealed · The 2022-26 mandate</p>
      <h1>Eight parties, five behaviours</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Sweden has eight parties on the 2026 ballot. The chamber record
        of 2022-26 shows five behavioural entities. One of them &mdash;
        the four-party Tidö bloc, voting and reasoning as one &mdash;
        formed during this mandate. This is the evidence.
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      When voters compare parties they reach for the same shortcuts: a
      left-right slider, an alliance label, a coalition map. Each assumes
      the eight parties on the 2026 ballot still mean what they
      meant when they were elected. The 2022-26 parliamentary record
      suggests they don't.
    </p>

    <p>
      One claim, in evidence. The 2026 ballot lists eight parties. On
      the chamber record of the mandate, those eight resolve to five
      behavioural entities:
    </p>

    <ul class="entity-list">
      <li><strong>The Tidö bloc.</strong> M, KD, L and SD, voting and
      reasoning together as one. The fusion happened during the
      mandate, asymmetrically &mdash; SD moved toward the cabinet, M's
      vocabulary moved toward SD.</li>
      <li><strong>Socialdemokraterna.</strong> Alone, behaviourally as
      well as politically, occupying its own arm of the chamber map.</li>
      <li><strong>V and MP together.</strong> The only opposition pair
      that both votes and reasons alike. A genuine bloc, not a
      coalition of convenience.</li>
      <li><strong>Centerpartiet, behaviourally on the opposition
      side.</strong> Nominally at the centre of Swedish politics, but
      voting with S on 91 % of chamber votes and clustering with V and
      MP on the chamber map.</li>
      <li><strong>The Liberalerna defectors.</strong> Eight of the
      twelve top behavioural defectors in the Riksdag are L members
      whose voting record sits closer to KD or M than to L. The L
      caucus is structurally inside the KD and M clusters.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The article walks the five at party-mean level, then asks how
      the Tidö entity formed during the mandate, then turns to the
      eight 2022 manifestos to see where the parties still differ on
      paper, then holds the two layers against each other. The data:
      two and a half thousand chamber votes, eleven thousand written
      reservations, fifty thousand speeches, and the eight 2022
      manifestos &mdash; read as evidence rather than rhetoric.
    </p>

    <h2>The chamber map</h2>

    <p>
      Every chamber vote in the mandate, member by member, projected
      into two dimensions by PCA on the 424-by-2,501 vote matrix.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/01_behavioural_map.png`} alt="Behavioural map of the Riksdag based on voting patterns, 2022-2026" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The Riksdag 2022-2026, projected into two dimensions via PCA on
        the voting matrix. The first axis (PC1, 46 % of variance)
        separates the Tidö government bloc from the opposition. The
        second (PC2, 13.5 %) splits the opposition into a
        Socialdemokrat arm and a V/MP/C arm. Centerpartiet sits at the
        centre of the first axis but well down on the second:
        geographically centrist, behaviourally close to the soft left.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Four of the five entities are visible at party-mean level on this
      map:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Tidö</strong> &mdash; M, KD, L and SD packed tightly
      on the right of PC1.</li>
      <li><strong>S</strong> &mdash; alone on the upper left, in its
      own arm of PC2.</li>
      <li><strong>V and MP</strong> &mdash; together on the lower
      diagonal, V furthest from the centre on the bloc axis.</li>
      <li><strong>C</strong> &mdash; at the geographic centre of PC1
      but well down PC2, sitting with V and MP rather than between
      cabinet and opposition.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      What is worth noting is what is <em>not</em> on the map: no
      coalition cutting across the cabinet/opposition line, no
      realignment from Centerpartiet onto the cabinet side. The
      within-opposition split on PC2 is real &mdash; S sits clearly
      apart from V/MP/C, which is what makes the second axis worth
      13 % of variance &mdash; but it stays on the opposition side of
      the bloc line.
    </p>

    <p>
      The practical reading is about Centerpartiet. C sits at the
      centre of PC1 but in the V/MP arm on PC2; across the mandate, C
      voted with S on 91 % of chamber votes. A vote for C is a vote
      on the opposition side of the bloc line, not in the centre of it.
    </p>

    <h3>The same pattern, per topic</h3>

    <p>
      The cluster pattern is not an artefact of a single PCA. It
      repeats across substantively different policy topics:
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/33_per_topic_stance.png`} alt="Vote stance per party per topic, top 20 by cross-party variance" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mean vote stance per (party, topic). +1 = the party consistently
        voted Yes on points classified into that topic, -1 = consistently
        No, 0 = mixed. Topics are sorted left-to-right by cross-party
        variance, so the most polarising appear first.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Migration is the single most differentiating topic by some
      distance, followed by international aid, pharmaceuticals and
      dental care, climate, and schools. The same alignment recurs in
      each: V, MP and C on one side; M, KD, L, SD on the other; S in
      between.
    </p>

    <h3>Vote and reasoning</h3>

    <p>
      Voting together is not the same as reasoning together. For every
      party pair, we have a vote-stance similarity from the chamber
      record and a reasoning similarity from the topic-centred cosine
      between reservation reasoning vectors. The two correlate at
      roughly r = 0.55, but the residuals are where the interesting
      pairs live.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/34_vote_vs_reasoning.png`} alt="Party pair vote similarity vs reasoning similarity" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Each point is one of the 28 party pairs. X axis: similarity of
        how the two parties voted across all 2,501 chamber votes.
        Y axis: similarity of how the two parties reasoned in their
        reservations and majority opinions, with the parliamentary
        average per topic subtracted. The dashed line is the cross-pair
        trend. Pairs above the line argue more alike than they vote.
        Pairs below vote together but reason apart.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Three pairs are worth naming, each one confirming or qualifying
      one of the five entities:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>V and MP: vote alike and argue alike.</strong> The only
        above-trend pair in the opposition. V and MP are a genuine bloc
        on both vote and reasoning evidence &mdash; the third entity,
        confirmed at the reasoning layer.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>M and SD: vote alike and argue alike.</strong> Vote
        similarity 0.83, reasoning similarity above the trend line. Not
        just SD voting with the cabinet but M's reasoning register
        having shifted toward SD's. The Tidö entity at the reasoning
        layer, not just the vote layer.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>S and C: vote alike, argue apart.</strong> S and C vote
        together 91 % of the time, more than any other non-cabinet pair,
        but they sit substantially below the reasoning trend. They
        share opposition arithmetic without sharing the underlying
        values vocabulary. A marriage of convenience, not a sixth
        entity.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Four of the five entities are now on the map at party-mean
      level. The fifth &mdash; the Liberalerna defectors &mdash; only
      appears once we go below party averages. We'll get to them after
      the story of how the Tidö entity formed.
    </p>

    <h2>How four parties became one</h2>

    <p>
      The party positions above are averages across the whole mandate.
      The story is how they got there.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/07_tido_collapse.png`} alt="The Tidö bloc collapsing into a single cluster" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The four parties of the Tidö bloc (M, KD, L and SD as a
        support party), per parliamentary year. The mean pairwise
        distance between their centroids falls from 9.08 in 2022/23 to
        0.43 in 2025/26. By the election year the four points sit on
        top of one another.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The cabinet trio has always voted as a unit by definition. The
      collapse is therefore SD moving toward the cabinet, not the
      cabinet moving toward SD. And the movement accelerated as the
      election approached.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/08_agreement_trend.png`} alt="Tidö bloc agreement trend over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left panel.</strong> Share of chamber votes where the
        entire Tidö bloc voted unanimously. The share rose from 73 %
        in 2024/25 to 98 % in 2025/26, in step with the start of the
        election year.
        <strong>Right panel.</strong> The rise is driven entirely by
        SD aligning with the cabinet's positions, not the cabinet
        adjusting toward SD.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Of the 687 chamber votes in 2025/26, SD deviated from the cabinet
      in eleven.
    </p>

    <p class="pullquote">
      SD's filed reservations fell from 574 in 2024/25 to 17 in 2025/26.
      The party of opposition stopped opposing on the record, one year
      before the election.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/21_sd_reservation_collapse.png`} alt="SD reservations per parliamentary year, the election-year collapse" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Reservations filed per party and parliamentary year. The thick
        yellow line is SD: 749, 402, 574, 17. The opposition parties
        rise or hold steady. The cabinet parties (M, KD, L) are
        excluded as, being the majority, they file very few.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>Votes without signatures</h3>

    <p>
      The vote convergence preceded the reservation collapse. For most
      of the mandate SD voted alongside the cabinet without co-signing
      the cabinet's alternative proposals.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/30_temporal_coauthorship.png`} alt="Reservation co-authorship over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left.</strong> Opposition parties co-sign reservations
        with each other continuously, with V-MP the tightest pair (0.26
        to 0.37). All three pairs tick up in 2025/26, the election year,
        as opposition activity intensifies.
        <strong>Right.</strong> SD with the three cabinet parties:
        co-authorship is structurally zero for the first three years.
        In the election year a single uptick: KD-SD rises to 0.24,
        while M-SD and L-SD remain flat. The first co-signed
        reservations between SD and a cabinet party appear only when
        the election is six months away.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Across the entire mandate SD has co-signed exactly three
      reservations with a cabinet party (all KD-SD), out of nearly
      eleven thousand reservations filed. They vote with the cabinet on
      78 % of chamber votes across the mandate, rising to 98 % in the
      election year, but they do not put their name to joint
      alternative proposals until the election is six months away. SD
      votes alongside; for three years, it does not co-author.
    </p>

    <p>
      What this implies at the ballot box depends on which register one
      weights. Counted in votes, SD has been a cabinet party throughout
      the mandate. Counted in signatures on joint reservations, SD
      spent three years standing apart from the cabinet, then aligned
      only as the election approached.
    </p>

    <h3>M and SD: shared vocabulary, not just shared votes</h3>

    <p>
      M and SD voted alike during the mandate, and M's reservation
      register drifted measurably toward SD's. The boundary between
      cabinet and support party has thinned from both sides: SD moving
      into the cabinet's positions, M moving into SD's vocabulary. By
      the election year they are, on the parliamentary record, one
      entity.
    </p>

    <h3>The fifth entity: the L defectors</h3>

    <p>
      Party averages can hide individual behaviour. Compute, for each
      MP, the ratio of their distance to their own party's centroid
      against their distance to the nearest other party. A ratio above
      1 means the MP votes more like another party than their own.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/31_defectors.png`} alt="Top behavioural defectors over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The 12 MPs with the highest distance-to-own-party /
        distance-to-nearest-other-party ratio, on a log scale. The
        dashed line marks equidistance. A ratio of 5x means the MP is
        five times further from their own party's centroid than from
        another party's.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Eight of the top twelve are Liberalerna MPs whose voting record
      sits closer to KD or M than to L. The collapse seen at
      party-mean level is also a collapse at the MP level: the L
      caucus is structurally inside the Christian-Democratic and
      Moderate clusters. This is the fifth entity &mdash; an L caucus
      that, on the floor, votes the cabinet's positions even when L is
      the formal author of the vote.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/28_centroid_trajectories.png`} alt="Each party's voting centroid drift across four parliamentary years" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Each party's voting centroid across the four parliamentary
        years. Dot size grows with year. The arrow on the last segment
        points to where the party landed in the election year. Beyond
        the Tidö story, MP drifted up PC2, V drifted further from the
        centre on PC1, and S barely moved at all.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      By 2026 the four Tidö parties on the ballot are, on the record
      of this mandate, one option. A vote for any of the four is a
      vote for the same package.
    </p>

    <h2>The manifesto layer: where the eight are still eight</h2>

    <p>
      Voted behaviour collapses the eight parties to five entities.
      Manifestos do not. Read as text, the eight 2022 manifestos remain
      eight separate documents &mdash; but the documents are not
      symmetrical, and the asymmetry matters before any comparison.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/36_manifesto_coverage.png`} alt="Manifesto topical coverage per party" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left.</strong> Sentence count per (party, topic) for the
        eight 2022 manifestos, after assigning each sentence to its
        nearest of 28 policy topics. Topics are ordered left to right by
        total coverage across parties.
        <strong>Right.</strong> Number of topics where the party has at
        least five on-topic manifesto sentences. SD covers 19 of 28
        topics; KD covers 1.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      SD's 21,000-word manifesto registers meaningful content in 19 of
      the 28 policy topics; KD's 1,600-word manifesto covers one. Any
      cross-party manifesto comparison is sensitive to which topics
      each party chose to write about. With that caveat in place, the
      manifestos can be read along four dimensions: what is wrong
      (diagnosis), what should be (end state), how to get there
      (mechanism), and the values behind the answers.
    </p>

    <h3>Diagnosis: what is wrong with Sweden</h3>

    <p>
      Two parties are notably diagnosis-heavy:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Sverigedemokraterna.</strong> 12.8 % of substantive
        sentences are problem statements, by some distance the largest
        share of the eight. They diagnose crime, migration costs, and
        cultural fragmentation.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Kristdemokraterna.</strong> 10.9 % of substantive
        sentences are diagnostic, despite the shortest manifesto of
        the eight (1.6k words total). Per word, KD is the most
        concerned with What Is Wrong. They diagnose family fragility,
        mental health, and weakened community.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      At the other end, Centerpartiet is the most forward-looking
      (4.7 % diagnosis): a manifesto light on critique, heavy on
      policy detail. Vänsterpartiet diagnoses inequality and
      exploitation (9.9 %); Moderaterna diagnoses weak state
      institutions and the lack of consequences (7.5 %).
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_diagnosis.png`} alt="Diagnosis similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Cosine similarity between the party-level mean embedding of all
        diagnosis sentences. SD and KD share the language of crisis
        most strongly. V and MP cluster on inequality and climate
        framing. The cabinet trio (M, KD, L) does not cluster on
        diagnosis as cleanly as it does on the vote record, because
        the three parties describe different problems even when they
        end up voting for the same solutions.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      One pattern foreshadows the chamber story: SD and M describe
      Sweden's problems in more similar language than M and L do, even
      though M and L share a cabinet. The fusion was visible in the
      diagnostic vocabulary before it was visible on the floor.
    </p>

    <h3>End state: what should Sweden be</h3>

    <p>
      End-state sentences are the aspirational core of a manifesto:
      "we want a Sweden where ...", "every child should ...", "a
      society in which ...". The shares differ by almost a factor of
      six between the most and least vision-heavy manifestos.
    </p>

    <table class="data-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Party</th><th>End-state share</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>MP</td><td>17.0 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C</td><td>10.5 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>L</td><td>10.4 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>V</td><td>7.9 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>S</td><td>7.5 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>M</td><td>6.2 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>SD</td><td>5.7 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>KD</td><td>3.1 %</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>
      Miljöpartiet is unusually structured around vision: nearly one in
      five sentences describes a future to aspire to. KD is the
      opposite, a short manifesto built almost entirely from critique
      with very thin description of what they want instead. SD lands
      near the bottom too, which fits the diagnosis-heavy reading: a
      manifesto more invested in naming what has gone wrong than in
      describing what should replace it.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_end_state.png`} alt="End-state similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        End-state language similarity. The pattern flattens. Most
        parties land at 0.78 to 0.90 with one another. The aspirational
        vocabulary of Swedish politics ("trygghet för alla", "ett
        starkt Sverige", "en hållbar framtid") is broadly shared, even
        between parties who agree on almost nothing else.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      End-state similarity is a poor discriminator. If two manifestos
      describe the future Sweden they want in similar words, that says
      very little about whether they propose to get there in similar
      ways. The differences live downstream.
    </p>

    <h3>Mechanism: by what means</h3>

    <p>
      Mechanism is the most concrete and most differentiated question.
      Moderaterna's manifesto is the most mechanism-heavy of the eight
      (20.5 % of substantive sentences): a fifth of its content is
      proposals using verbs like <em>höja</em>, <em>skärpa</em>,
      <em>reformera</em>, <em>införa</em>. The cabinet's policy
      register is built into the manifesto.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_mechanism.png`} alt="Mechanism similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mechanism-language similarity. M, KD and L cluster as expected,
        the cabinet's shared register. C and L cluster slightly
        separately, with a tilt toward market vocabulary. SD sits
        somewhat apart from M, KD, L despite voting almost identically
        with them on the floor.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The cabinet trio and SD vote identically but describe their
      mechanisms in different vocabulary. M, KD and L use
      administrative-procedural language (<em>reformera</em>,
      <em>tilldela</em>, <em>tillsyn</em>). SD uses outcome language
      (<em>Sverige måste</em>, <em>det räcker nu</em>, <em>vi ska vända
      utvecklingen</em>). Their proposals do the same thing. Their
      manifestos describe them differently.
    </p>

    <p>
      Mechanism preferences also drift inside parliament. Four
      mechanism dimensions, each with a short curated word list:
      market versus regulation, prevention versus punishment, central
      state versus local, universal versus targeted welfare. Each
      chamber speech is scored on each axis from the relative
      frequency of the two vocabularies.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/29_temporal_how_lexicon.png`} alt="Mechanism vocabulary per party over four parliamentary years" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Four mechanism axes, per party, per parliamentary year. Each
        line is one party's relative frequency of the two vocabularies
        on that axis.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Two patterns stand out:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>The prevention-punishment axis swung sharply.</strong>
        Centerpartiet and Miljöpartiet both moved 0.28 to 0.30 units
        toward punishment vocabulary across the mandate. These are
        the two parties one might least expect to shift in this
        direction. The Tidö parties, who already used more punishment
        vocabulary at the start, moved much less. The opposition
        adopted the framing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Moderaterna's market vocabulary grew (+0.16) while
        Liberalerna's shrank (-0.11).</strong> The cabinet's two
        ostensibly market-friendly parties moved in opposite
        directions on the market-regulation axis. M's market register
        rose; L's fell as L's chamber speech took on more
        administrative vocabulary.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Read as a forecast, the drift is the point. The C and MP that
      voters chose in 2022 used less punishment vocabulary than the C
      and MP on the 2026 ballot. Vocabulary shifts are not policy
      commitments, but they are early signals of where each party's
      centre of gravity is moving.
    </p>

    <h3>Values: signature vocabularies</h3>

    <p>
      Each manifesto invokes a recognisable set of values. Some are
      widely shared (frihet, demokrati). Others belong distinctively
      to one or two parties.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/22_manifesto_values.png`} alt="Value frequency heatmap" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-1000-word frequency of value vocabulary across the eight
        2022 manifestos, z-scored across parties. Red = invokes that
        value more than average; blue = less. Values are sorted
        left-to-right by how distinctively one party owns them.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The signature values come through cleanly:
    </p>

    <ul class="signature-values">
      <li><strong>M</strong> · ordning (+2.2 σ). No other value
        distinguishes M as strongly. The Moderate manifesto is built
        around the lack-of-order diagnosis.</li>
      <li><strong>KD</strong> · trygghet (+2.1 σ), ansvar (+1.6 σ),
        staten (+1.4 σ). A statist-conservative cluster, the most
        distinct of all eight.</li>
      <li><strong>C</strong> · jämställdhet (+2.0 σ), marknaden
        (+1.8 σ), individens (+1.6 σ). Liberal in the European sense,
        wholly different from KD despite sitting in the same camp.</li>
      <li><strong>MP</strong> · rättvisa (+2.0 σ), klimat (+1.9 σ),
        solidaritet (+1.2 σ). MP and V share a value vocabulary; on
        climate, MP stands alone.</li>
      <li><strong>L</strong> · frihet (+1.7 σ), valfrihet (+1.7 σ),
        demokrati (+1.6 σ). Classical liberal, value-vocabulary closer
        to C than to KD even though L sits in the cabinet with KD.</li>
      <li><strong>SD</strong> · nationell identitet (+1.8 σ),
        tradition (+1.4 σ), staten (+1.2 σ). The most predictable
        profile in the table.</li>
      <li><strong>V</strong> · jämlikhet (+1.7 σ), solidaritet (+1.6 σ),
        kollektivets (+1.5 σ). Class-based vocabulary, also
        predictable.</li>
      <li><strong>S</strong> · tradition (+1.8 σ), öppenhet (+1.6 σ),
        kollektivets (+1.6 σ). The surprise of the table.
        Socialdemokraterna invoke "tradition" more frequently per word
        than SD does. The vocabulary of the folkhem reads as
        traditional when measured.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The pairings make sense. V and S share the kollektivets register.
      C and L share the marknaden / valfrihet register. SD and KD share
      the trygghet / staten / tradition register. MP stands alone on
      klimat. The hardest party to summarise in a single value is M,
      whose value vocabulary is sparse compared to the others. Its
      manifesto reads as mechanism-first, value-second.
    </p>

    <h3>Coherence: do the four layers fit together?</h3>

    <p>
      Diagnosis, end state, mechanism and values are separable as
      questions. They need not be coherent inside a given manifesto.
      For each party, embed every diagnosis sentence, every end-state
      sentence and every mechanism sentence into the same SBERT vector
      space, average per element, and compute cosine similarity
      between each pair.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/38_party_coherence.png`} alt="Within-party cosine between element vectors" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        For each party, pairwise cosine between the mean embedding of
        their diagnosis sentences, end-state sentences, and mechanism
        sentences. Higher means the three element vocabularies look
        more alike. KD is excluded for having too few end-state
        sentences (n=4).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Two patterns appear in this otherwise tight figure.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>End-state and mechanism are always closer to each
        other than either is to diagnosis.</strong> For every party,
        the green bar is taller than the orange. The language of "what
        we want" and the language of "what we will do" share
        vocabulary in a way that the language of "what is wrong" does
        not. This is a structural fact about Swedish political
        writing, not about any one party.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>SD has the highest internal coherence (mean 0.86); MP
        has the lowest (0.78).</strong> SD's long, technical manifesto
        reads as one document about one thing. MP's manifesto sits
        across more vocabularies (climate language, rights language,
        mechanism language) that overlap less. The cross-party spread
        is small but consistent: parties with longer, single-author
        manifestos read as more internally coherent than those that
        read like compilations.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The gap: stated and revealed</h2>

    <p>
      Two layers, two readings of the same eight parties. The voted
      record collapses them to five entities; the manifestos keep them
      at eight. The most useful question is therefore: how well does
      each party's manifesto still describe its parliamentary work?
    </p>

    <p>
      To measure this, we embedded each manifesto sentence into the
      same vector space as the party's reservation reasoning during
      the mandate, assigned each sentence to one of 28 policy topics
      via cosine similarity, and compared within-topic-within-party
      cells (≥5 manifesto sentences per cell). Without the topic
      restriction the comparison would mostly measure register
      differences (cabinet parties write polished committee
      formulations; opposition parties write technical reservations).
      The topic restriction removes most of that confound.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/26_topic_matched_gap.png`} alt="Topic-matched stated-vs-revealed gap per party" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-party mean cosine between manifesto and reservation
        language across covered topics, with the number of comparable
        topics in parentheses. Higher = the party speaks more
        similarly in its manifesto as in its parliamentary work.
        KD (n=1) and MP (n=3) have too few topics with sufficient
        manifesto material to interpret reliably; their bars are
        shown but should be read with caution.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The headline pattern, with the small-sample parties set aside:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>L is the most consistent</strong> (0.76 mean across 9
        topics). Their manifesto language and their reservation
        language describe policy in the same register &mdash; though
        the L defectors story above adds a caveat: the manifesto and
        the committee work line up, but the floor vote sits closer to
        KD and M.</li>
      <li><strong>V has the largest gap</strong> (0.61 across 11
        topics). Their manifesto is aspirational and rhetorical; their
        reservations are technical legal critiques. The within-topic
        gap is real and structural, not a sample artefact.</li>
      <li><strong>SD is unexpectedly consistent</strong> (0.71 across
        19 topics). A long, technical manifesto and a long track
        record of detailed reservation work, written in compatible
        registers, until the election year.</li>
    </ul>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/27_party_topic_gap_matrix.png`} alt="Party by topic gap matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        One cell per (party, topic). Pale cells = the party speaks
        similarly in its manifesto and in its parliamentary work on
        that topic; dark cells = the two diverge. Topics are sorted by
        mean divergence across parties.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The topics that diverge most across parties are civil emergency
      preparedness, industrial policy and health care. The pattern is
      the same in each case: manifestos describe these as questions of
      resilience, growth and dignity, while reservations describe them
      as specific clauses, allocations and amendments. The topics
      where the gap is smallest are the ones where manifestos already
      wrote in policy-instrument language: tax (where manifestos
      already state specific rates), defence (where everyone uses Nato
      procurement vocabulary), and migration.
    </p>

    <h3>Inside parliament, two registers</h3>

    <p>
      Manifesto is one register. Parliament has two of its own: the
      chamber speech, oral and often delivered without notes, and the
      written reservation, drafted by party staff and polished. If a
      party speaks the same way in both, its parliamentary register is
      internally consistent. If the two diverge, the chamber persona
      and the committee persona differ.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/32_speech_vs_reservation.png`} alt="Per-party speech vs reservation cosine similarity" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-party mean speech reasoning vector against mean reservation
        reasoning vector, restricted to (party, topic) cells covered by
        both. Higher = the party uses the same vocabulary in chamber
        speeches as in written reservations.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The four opposition parties and Sverigedemokraterna all land in
      a tight 0.87 to 0.89 band. Inside parliament, each of these five
      parties speaks the same way regardless of register. The cabinet
      bars are hatched because the cabinet writes almost no
      reservations: L has reservation material in only 8 topic cells,
      KD in 11, M in 8. The bars are technically computable but the
      sample is too small to read as a finding.
    </p>

    <p>
      The opposition's internal consistency matters for one
      interpretation. The largest manifesto-versus-reservation gap is
      V's, not because V is register-inconsistent inside parliament
      &mdash; V's speech and writing track each other &mdash; but
      because V's manifesto reads in a different register than its
      parliamentary work. The drift is between manifesto and
      parliament, not within parliament.
    </p>

    <h2>For a 2026 voter</h2>

    <p>
      The article describes the Riksdag. It does not score parties
      against each other and it does not tell you who to vote for.
      What it can do is route you by issue, by trust register, and by
      what the data cannot answer.
    </p>

    <h3>Where does your priority issue live?</h3>

    <p>
      Topics differ enormously in how much they separate parties. The
      per-topic figure above routes a voter by issue:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Migration.</strong> The sharpest split in the chamber.
        V, MP and C on one side; M, KD, L and SD on the other; S in
        between. If migration is decisive, the side of the bloc line
        determines the outcome; within-side party choice changes
        little.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>International aid (bistånd).</strong> The same 4-vs-4
        alignment as migration, with no within-bloc nuance. The
        opposition defends the budget; the cabinet plus SD cuts it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Climate.</strong> V and MP are the distinctive
        pro-climate voices (klimat is MP's signature value); SD is the
        distinctive outlier on the other side. The cabinet trio is
        mixed. For climate as a decisive issue, V or MP carries the
        most distinctive vote.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Schools, pharmaceuticals, dental care.</strong>
        Welfare-expansion topics. Opposition for, cabinet plus SD
        against. The cluster pattern matches migration.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Anything else.</strong> Cross-party variance drops
        sharply outside the top five most polarising topics. If your
        decisive issue is not on the polarising list above, the
        four-year record suggests party choice will affect that issue
        less than your other criteria might.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Which document do you trust?</h3>

    <p>
      A manifesto is what a party writes when it does not have to act.
      The parliamentary record is what it does when it does. The two
      do not agree about every party. Vänsterpartiet's manifesto is
      the most aspirational; its reservations are the most technical
      &mdash; if you weight aspiration heavily, the manifesto sets
      your expectation, but the record will keep undershooting it.
      Liberalerna's manifesto matches its committee work closely; but
      the L caucus's floor votes sit nearer to KD and M than to the L
      manifesto. The four Tidö manifestos each promise something
      distinctive; the chamber record collapses those promises into
      one. Each of these mismatches is worth knowing before you
      weight one document over the other.
    </p>

    <h3>Does silence in a manifesto count against a party?</h3>

    <p>
      Kristdemokraterna's 1,600-word manifesto registers meaningful
      content in 1 of 28 policy topics; Sverigedemokraterna's
      21,000-word manifesto covers 19. When a party does not write
      about an issue you care about, that may mean they accept the
      consensus, they have not formed a position, or they would
      rather be evaluated on something else. The analysis cannot tell
      you which; only you can decide which interpretation matters
      more for your own choice.
    </p>

    <h3>What the data cannot answer</h3>

    <p>
      Two questions sit outside the chamber record entirely. The
      first: whether the Tidö fusion is responsible coalition support
      or the absorption of a fourth party into a three-party cabinet
      without the public accountability of a cabinet seat. The data
      tells you the fusion is real, structural and asymmetric &mdash;
      SD moved toward the cabinet, not the other way around &mdash;
      but the interpretation is yours. The second: whether the
      pattern of this mandate will continue, reverse, or splinter.
      All this analysis is about a closed four-year period. Behaviour
      in the next mandate is for the next voters to read.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <p class="method-note">
      All analysis is based on reproducible methods over public data
      from <a href="https://data.riksdagen.se">data.riksdagen.se</a>
      and the eight 2022 party manifestos from the SND "Vi vill"
      archive. Source code and full method write-up at
      <a href="https://github.com/freol35241/ps-sverige">GitHub</a>.
      No interviews, no surveys, no subjective judgements beyond
      those needed to define keyword pools, topic clusters and
      vocabulary lists, which are openly documented in the code.
    </p>
  </article>
